Instance versus Fargate launch types.

The container service runs the same task definition under two launch types, and the difference is who owns the host.

With the instance launch type, you manage the instances, you pick the type and image and can connect in, you pay per instance-hour, and you pay even when zero tasks run; in exchange you can use special hardware or custom kernels. With the Fargate launch type, AWS owns the host and it's invisible, you pay per task's see-pee-you and memory by the second, and there's no idle cost and nothing to patch. Fargate sizing uses discrete see-pee-you and memory pairs; you pick a valid pair and AWS picks the host.

The general rule: start with Fargate for simplicity, and move to the instance launch type with savings plans once you've grown into steady, predictable utilization where per-hour math beats per-second.
